<?xml version='1.0' encoding='UTF-8'?>
<ecoSpold xmlns="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02" xmlns:xsi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XMLSchema-instance" xsi:schemaLocation="http://www.EcoInvent.org/EcoSpold02 ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02.xsd http://www.EcoInvent.org/UsedUserMasterData ../../schemas/datasets/EcoSpold02UserMasterData.xsd">
  <childActivityDataset>
    <activityDescription>
      <activity specialActivityType="0" id="21bc1583-77fb-5322-8f95-40fab8f9af27" activityNameId="d76b8cde-495f-4163-b019-fdaa46de46e8" parentActivityId="481c41dc-b021-47a6-9dbe-5ade8b7e327d" inheritanceDepth="-1" type="1">
        <activityName xml:lang="en">sodium cyanide production</activityName>
        <includedActivitiesStart xml:lang="en">The activity starts when the raw materials enter the process.</includedActivitiesStart>
        <includedActivitiesEnd xml:lang="en">The activity ends with sodium cyanide being ready for further transformation or transportation at the production site gate. Materials entering the process are included as well as energy uses, infrastructure and emissions.
</includedActivitiesEnd>
        <generalComment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The functional unit represent 1 kg of sodium cyanide. The production of sodium cyanides is the same worldwide, comprising of a simple neutralization reaction between a weak acid and a strong base, as follows:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">HCN + NaOH → NaCN + H2O, ΔH = 460 kJ</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">Pure sodium cyanide NaCN (CAS: 143-33-9) is a white crystalline solid commonly called white cyanide, that is readily soluble in water. Sodium and potassium cyanides are often called “alkaline cyanides” because they render water alkaline pH when dissolved (Ulmann, 2004). At the same time, alkali metal cyanides are sensitive to humitity which contains carbon dioxide, which is a weak acid in aqueous solution. Furthermore, alkili cyanides attracted significant interest for the recovery of precous metals. For example, in 1840, the electroplating process for gold and silver was developed and acted as major driver for the consumption of sodium cyanide. Other large single uses of sodium cyanide considered the electroplating of zinc, copper, brass, and cadmium (Kirk, 2004). Sodium cyanide could also find several uses in the chemical industry, such as an additive (&lt;5%) in dyes, including optical brighteners, agricultural chemicals, pharmaceutricals, chelating or sequestering agents. Finally, sodium cyanide, along with CaCl2, find also used in the treatment of wood chips.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">In this dataset, the raw material inputs, and process-specific material exchanges, are modelled with a generic stoichiometry-based tool, using literature or estimated yields. The emissions are modelled with a default value, which is estimated  based on losses, unreacted chemicals, among others. At the same time, the energy consumption is based on data from literature sources.  Finally, the auxiliary (i.e., cooling water and infrastructure) exchanges are modelled with a default value based on industry data from literature sources.   For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Ullmann's encyclopedia of industrial chemistry (2004).</text>
        </generalComment>
      </activity>
      <classification classificationId="28f738cc-bb73-48f8-b633-f83fb9bc5ddc">
        <classificationSystem xml:lang="en">ISIC rev.4 ecoinvent</classificationSystem>
        <classificationValue xml:lang="en">2011:Manufacture of basic chemicals</classificationValue>
      </classification>
      <geography geographyId="0723d252-7e2a-11de-9820-0019e336be3a">
        <shortname xml:lang="en">RER</shortname>
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The inventory is modelled for Europe. The main material inputs and outputs of this activity are generated with on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields.  Furthermore, the source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The dataset could also be considered as not geography-specific, and thus, valid for a broader geographical coverage.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Kim, Seungdo, and Michael Overcash "Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate‐to‐gate information for life cycle assessment." Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology: International Research in Process, Environmental &amp; Clean Technology 78.9 (2003): 995-1005. </text>
        </comment>
      </geography>
      <technology technologyLevel="3">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">Production from sodium hydroxide and hydrogen cyanide by neutralization, the efficiency of which is very high (if the raw materials are sufficiently pure (Kirk, 2004)), attaining a yield &gt;99%, and only minimal losses occur (Ulmann, 2004).</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">Reaction:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">HCN + NaOH → NaCN + H2O, ΔH = 460 kJ</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">Modern commercial facilities use purified anhydrous liquid hydrogen cyanide as raw material, that reacts with a 50% solution of sodium hydroxide. Furthermore, high capacity plants generate high purity sodium cyanide via evaporation of water and crystallization (Kirk, 2004). A crucial aspect is the system's control to maximize the sodium formate formation by avoiding the hydrogen cyanide polymer formation.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">In this dataset, a yield of 99% was assumed, as per the literature mentioned above.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Kirk, Raymond E., Donald F. Othmer, and Charles A. Mann. "Encyclopedia of Chemical Technology." 2004.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Ullmann's encyclopedia of industrial chemistry (2004).</text>
        </comment>
      </technology>
      <timePeriod startDate="2003-01-01" endDate="2023-12-31" isDataValidForEntirePeriod="true">
        <comment>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="0">The time period spans from the earliest year from which at least one of the input values was obtained until 2022, but overall form the most realistic picture of the production. Besides, the activity is partly generated, in terms of material inputs and outputs, based on a generic stoichiometry-based model, using literature or estimated yields, which does not expect to change over time.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="1">The source of information for the heat and electricity inputs is literature data (from 2003) for the specific technology. Finally, the main source of information for the values for water (process and cooling), nitrogen, chemical factory is industry data from the GENDORF Chemical Park. The values are a 5-year average of data from 2015 to 2019 published by the GENDORF Chemical Park, which is based in Germany and produced an average of 2462760 tonnes of chemical substances in the years 2015-2019. The end time period is therefore set based on the years from Gendorf reference.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="2">For more information on the calculations refer to the sampling procedure and in the comments of the exchanges.</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="3">References:</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="4">Hischier, R. (2005) Establishing Life Cycle Inventories of Chemicals Based on Differing Data Availability (9 pp). The International Journal of Life Cycle Assessment, Volume 10, Issue 1, pp 59-67. 10.1065/lca2004.10.181.7 </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="5">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2016, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit</text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="6">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2017, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="7">Chemiepark GENDORF, Umwelterklärung 2020, https://www.gendorf.de/Nachbarn/Umweltschutz/Industrie%20und%20Nachhaltigkeit </text>
          <text xml:lang="en" index="8">Kim, Seungdo, and Michael Overcash "Energy in chemical manufacturing processes: gate‐to‐gate information for life cycle assessment." Journal of Chemical Technology &amp; Biotechnology: International Research in Process, Environmental &amp; Clean Technology 78.9 (2003): 995-1005. </text>
        </comment>
      </timePeriod>
      <macroEconomicScenario macroEconomicScenarioId="d9f57f0a-a01f-42eb-a57b-8f18d6635801">
        <name xml:lang="en">Business-as-Usual</name>
      </macroEconomicScenario>
    </activityDescription>
